** Time Management
*** Routines
    - Morning Check-ins
    - End of Day Updates
    - Meetings
    - Pre-meeting prep
    - Weekly Project Updates
    - one-on-ones with leadership
    - 90 minute pomodoros (kind of in tandem with the other alarms)

*** Flexibility
**** High Energy 
     - Requires a light calendar
     - Focus on ambiguity 
     - 1 major task + documentation
**** Medium Energy
     - Focus on completion, at the end of the week focus on what is 80% done
     - 3-4 medium tasks + collaboration
**** Low Energy
     - Sometimes due to a packed calendar
     - 5-8 small tasks + stay visible

*** Alarms
    - 10:30am - /Did I post an update?/
    - 2:00pm - /Am I working on the right thing?/
    - 4:30pm - /Post EOD update/
    - Calendar to have two alarms with built in "transition time". Always allow 15 minute breather between events on calendar.
    -- 15 minutes (start a brain dump so that it doesn't feel so bad to stop and allows us to pick up later)
    -- 5 minutes (stand up and say out loud DONE)

*** Triage
    - Intake during morning check-in (linear, slack, email, personal list)
    - Eisenhower matrix (Important + Urgency)
    -- Do Now
    -- Delegate 
    -- Schedule (This week, this month, this quarter, etc.)

*** Morning Check-in
    - Check linear for highest priority or quickest win
    - only aim to do ONE thing to consider the day a win

** Quick Dopamine Hits that add value
   - Review PR
   - close a small bug
   - Help out on slack

** When low energy and hyperfocus ends (require a time bound)
   - take a real world break
   - Review PRs
   - Organize linear
   - Update documentation

** Templates
   - Stakeholder updates for work
   - Weekly Progress summary
   - Monthly Progress summary
   - Meeting updates (pre-meeting prep)
   - Triage Templates

**** Triage Templates

     Response templates:
     - "I can help with this. Currently working on [X], can pick this up by [date]. Does that work?"
     - "This isn't in my current sprint. Let me check with [VP Eng] on priorities."
     - "I'm oncall, need to focus on that. Can [teammate] help or can this wait until [date]?"

** Goals
   - Share a "Today I Learned" in a public channel
   - Daily updates, don't leave the day without "speaking" to someone
   - Ask a question in a public channel 
   - Share Docs before its "done"
   - Talk in meetings, camera on
   - Regularly demo our work that we've done
   - Ask leadership questions in sync meetings rather than 1:1s
   - Keep a "brag doc" and/or a "brave moments doc"
   - Try working sessions to body double with work (we could even frame them as "office hours") 

** Preventative Protocols
   - Set alarms through out the day 
   - Everything we work on needs to be visible (even small tooling stuff). 
   - Personal projects NEED to wait until after hours or scheduled (20% time?) *this shouldn't happen until we prove discipline*

** Emergency Protocols
*** Going Silent
    - /few hours/ - Post an update NOW
    - /a whole day/ - Send update about yesterday and now, send manager an update as well directly acknowledging the silence

*** Wrong Priority
    - Acknowledge, and send update
    - Document learnings so some value can be gleaned 
    - Switch back to highest priority OR quickest win OR make case for this being priority. 




